04806nam a22006615i 9789633861462DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222016hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9789633861462  a(DE-B1597)633420  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aDX223 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a305.8914/970439qLOC2231 aMajtényi, Balázs, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Contemporary History of Exclusion :bThe Roma Issue in Hungary from 1945 to 2015 /cBalázs Majtényi, György Majtényi. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (250 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgment -- tIntroduction -- t"Comrades, If You Have a Heart..." The History of the Gypsy Issue, 1945-1961 -- t"Life Goes On..." The Hungarian Party-State and Policies of Assimilation -- tRoma Policy after the Regime Change -- tPanopticon: Roma Policy, 2010-2015 -- tSummary: Decades of Exclusion -- tBibliography -- tList of Photographs -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe volume presents the changing situation of the Roma in the second half of the 20th century and examines the politics of the Hungarian state regarding minorities by analyzing legal regulations, policy documents, archival sources and sociological surveys. In the first phase analyzed (1945-61), the authors show the efforts of forced assimilation by the communist state. The second phase (1961-89) began with the party resolution denying nationality status to the Roma. Gypsy culture was equivalent with culture of poverty that must be eliminated. Forced assimilation through labor activities continued. The Roma adapted to new conditions and yet kept their distinct identity. From the 1970s, Roma intellectuals began an emancipatory movement, and its legacy is felt until this day. Although the third phase (1989-2010) brought about freedoms and rights for the Roma, with large sums spent on various Roma-related programs, the situation on the ground nevertheless did not improve. Segregation and marginalization continues, and it is rampant. The authors powerfully conclude: while Roma became part of the political community, they are still not part of the national one. Subjects: Romanies-Hungary. Romanies-Hungary-Social conditions. Marginality, Social-Hungary. Romanies-Legal status, laws, etc.-Hungary. Minorities-Government policy-Hungary. Hungary-Ethnic relations. Hungary-Social policy.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aMarginality, SocialxHungary. 0aMarginality, SocialzHungary. 0aMinoritiesxGovernment policyxHungary. 0aMinoritiesxGovernment policyzHungary. 0aRomaniesxHungary. 0aRomaniesxLegal status, laws, etczHungary. 0aRomaniesxLegal status, laws, etc.xHungary. 0aRomaniesxLegal status, laws, etc.zHungary. 0aRomaniesxSocial conditionsxHungary. 0aRomanieszHungaryxSocial conditions. 0aRomanieszHungary. 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh  aCommunism, Human rights, Minorities, Modernization, Postcommunism, Romanies, Social policy.1 aMajtényi, György, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2016z978311078053640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633861462zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/documen